Pacific Coast Range

The Pacific Coast Range spans throughout the western coast of the United States, covering about 22,000 square miles. Bounded by the Klamath/Central California Coastal Mountains on the east and the Pacific Ocean to the west, this region is characterized by coastal headlands, marine terraces and its frequent landslides and wildfires. Although known for its ranges, the regions topography is inconsistent, having sea-level valleys or mountainous peaks reaching 1000 meters.

The Pacific Coast Range holds a warm-summer Mediterranean climate, characterized by mild/dry summers and cooler/wet winters, usually experiencing about 20 to 40 inches of rain per year. The rain maintains forests of Sitka spruce and Douglas-fir along the coast. Redwood forests are also prevalent, accompanied by various hardwoods. Common animals in this region include the mule deer and red-tailed hawk, but also contains unique species like the California spotted owl, Humboldt marten and mountain beaver.

The Pacific Coast Range in California is sparsely populated, with Eureka and Fort Bragg being some of the only significant population centers. Some notable areas and landmarks include Redwood National Park, Point Reyes, Eel River, and King Peak.
